---
import LessonLayout from '../../layouts/LessonLayout.astro';
---
<LessonLayout
  title="Setup & Hello World"
  track="young-builders"
  week={4}
  phase="Phase 2: Reachy Basics"
  duration="60 min"
  emoji="💻"
  objective="Connect to Reachy Mini and run your first Python command"
>
  <section class="lesson-section mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-builder-700 mb-3">🎯 Learning Objective</h2>
    <p class="bg-builder-50 border-l-4 border-builder-400 p-4 rounded-r-xl text-gray-700">
      You will set up the Reachy Mini SDK, understand the mock/simulator pattern, and run your first real robot command.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="lesson-section mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">🛠️ Setup Instructions</h2>
    <div class="bg-gray-900 text-green-300 rounded-xl p-5 text-sm space-y-2">
      <p># Install the Reachy Mini SDK</p>
      <p>pip install reachy-mini</p>
      <p></p>
      <p># Verify installation</p>
      <p>python -c "import reachy_mini; print('SDK installed!')"</p>
    </div>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-2">Don't worry if hardware isn't connected — our code always falls back to simulator mode.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="lesson-section mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">📋 Activity Steps</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div class="flex gap-4 items-start">
        <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-builder-500 text-white font-bold flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">1</span>
        <div><h3 class="font-bold">SDK Setup (15 min)</h3><p class="text-gray-600">Install reachy-mini. Run the verification command. If hardware is available, follow connection steps. If not, simulator mode is ready automatically.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex gap-4 items-start">
        <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-builder-500 text-white font-bold flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">2</span>
        <div><h3 class="font-bold">Hello World (20 min)</h3><p class="text-gray-600">Run the code below. Modify it to: change the greeting, add your name, make Reachy say 3 things.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex gap-4 items-start">
        <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-builder-500 text-white font-bold flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">3</span>
        <div><h3 class="font-bold">Explore the Mock API (15 min)</h3><p class="text-gray-600">Look at the ReachyMock class in the code. What methods does it have? What do you think each one does?</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex gap-4 items-start">
        <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-builder-500 text-white font-bold flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">4</span>
        <div><h3 class="font-bold">Design Challenge (10 min)</h3><p class="text-gray-600">Write a "startup sequence" for Reachy — what should it do when it first turns on? Code it!</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="lesson-section mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">💻 Code Snippet</h2>
    <pre is:raw class="bg-gray-900 text-green-300 rounded-xl p-5 overflow-x-auto text-sm leading-relaxed"><code># hello_reachy.py — Week 4: Young Builders
import time

class ReachyMock:
    """Full-featured Reachy simulator."""

    def __init__(self):
        self.mode = "simulator"
        print("🎮 Reachy Mock initialized (no hardware needed)")

    def say(self, text):
        print(f"🔊 Reachy says: '{text}'")
        time.sleep(0.5)

    def wave(self, arm="right", times=1):
        for i in range(times):
            print(f"🤚 Waving {arm} arm ({i+1}/{times})")
            time.sleep(0.3)

    def set_emotion(self, emotion):
        emotions = {"happy": "^‿^", "curious": "◔‿◔", "neutral": "•‿•"}
        eyes = emotions.get(emotion, "•‿•")
        print(f"😊 Eyes: {eyes} ({emotion})")

    def look_at(self, direction):
        print(f"👀 Looking: {direction}")
        time.sleep(0.3)

# Connect to Reachy (or use simulator)
try:
    from reachy_mini import ReachyMini
    robot = ReachyMini()
    print("✅ Connected to real Reachy Mini!")
except Exception as e:
    print(f"ℹ️  Hardware not found: {e}")
    robot = ReachyMock()

# Startup sequence
print("\n🤖 Running startup sequence...\n")
robot.set_emotion("neutral")
time.sleep(0.5)
robot.look_at("center")
robot.set_emotion("happy")
robot.say("Hello! I am Reachy Mini.")
robot.say("I am ready to learn with you!")
robot.wave(arm="right", times=2)
robot.say("Let's build something amazing together!")</code></pre>
  </section>

  <section class="lesson-section mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">💬 Reflection Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-3">
      <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-xl p-4"><p class="font-semibold text-blue-800">💭 Why is the mock/simulator pattern useful? When would real hardware matter more?</p></div>
      <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-xl p-4"><p class="font-semibold text-blue-800">💭 What would a good "startup sequence" for a home robot look like?</p></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="lesson-section mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">👪 Parent Tips</h2>
    <div class="bg-purple-50 border border-purple-200 rounded-xl p-5 text-gray-700">
      <p>💡 The try/except pattern is real professional Python. Your child is learning production-quality patterns from day one.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
</LessonLayout>
